						Egregiarum Mentium Sempiterna
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						hypothesis. Quid prodest Optimum Sine
						Effigie?
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				No one ever had enough good qualities, either in the mind, the body, or fortune.
				Therefore a more severe industriousness is necessary, along with an unceasing Actualization above all things.
				Crassus at home, Cicero in the forum, Cato in the senate, Caesar in the field: all wanted to the be [greatest of all].
				The eternal proposition of eminent minds. What is the point of being the best without a likeness?
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ironia Socratis mitigat Inuidiam, et mellificat [v]ia[m]. <!-- CG: Unsure of this last word. --> 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Socrates"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Viri est,
						quantiscunq[ue] potest modis,
						seipsum semper probare virum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Socrates' irony softens envy, and sweetens [the road].
				A man has however many ways he can use,
				always to test himself as a man.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
